%S A395762 1,0,1,0,5,1,0,5,10,1,0,5,60,15,1,0,5,160,165,20,1,0,5,360,1215,320,
%T A395762 25,1,0,5,760,5565,3920,525,30,1,0,5,1560,21015,35120,9025,780,35,1,0,
%U A395762 5,3160,72165,229520,123525,17280,1085,40,1
%N A395762 Array read by ascending antidiagonals: A(n, k) = Sum_{j=0..n} Stirling2(n, j)*5^j*(k)_j.
%C A395762 Base 5 polynomial collapse array for the iterated inverse Pascal operator.
%C A395762 In general, for any integer base b >=1, A_b(n, k) = Sum_{j=0..n} Stirling2(n, j)*b^j*(k)_j. Thus, this entry is the case b=5. The cases b=2,3,4 correspond respectively to A394444, A395570, and A395572.
%F A395762 Let D be the inverse Pascal operator: [D(f)]_m = Sum_{i=0..m} (-1)^(m - i)*binomial(m, i)*f(i). Then A(n, k) = [D^4(i^n*5^i)]_k = Sum_{j=0..n} Stirling2(n, j)*5^j*(k)_j.
%F A395762 For fixed k, the e.g.f. of A(n, k) in n is Sum_{n>=0} A(n, k)*u^n/n! = (1 + 5*(exp(u) - 1))^k.
%F A395762 A(n + 1, k) = k*(A(n, k) + 4*A(n, k - 1)) for k >= 1, with A(0, k) = 1 for k >= 0 and A(n, 0) = 0 for n > 0.
%F A395762 More generally, A_b(n, k) = Sum_{j=0..n} Stirling2(n, j)*b^j*(k)_j = Sum_{j=0..k} (-1)^(k - j)*binomial(k, j)*(b - 1)^(k - j)*b^j*j^n. For fixed k, the e.g.f. in n is Sum_{n>=0} A_b(n, k)*x^n/n! = (1 + b(e^x - 1))^k.
%e A395762 k | 0   1    2      3       4        5
%e A395762 n |--------------------------------------
%e A395762 0 | 1   1    1      1       1        1
%e A395762 1 | 0   5   10     15      20       25
